{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0181ooCZzTjFVLi1xwjmZFut","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture:\n\n1. Prometheus listens on port 9090 but the Service routes port 8000 → 9090\n2. The current Prometheus config only scrapes `localhost:9090` (itself - that's wrong since Prometheus doesn't expose its own metrics on 9090 by default this way, but it doesn't matter)\n3. RabbitMQ pods expose metrics on port 15692 at /metrics - confirmed working via headless DNS\n4. The headless service `rabbitmq-headless` allows addressing individual pods as:\n   - `rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n   - `rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n   - `rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n\nThe fix is straightforward: I need to update the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap to add a scrape job for RabbitMQ targeting all three pods via the headless service, then reload Prometheus using the lifecycle endpoint since `--web.enable-lifecycle` is already enabled. Since the namespace name is long, I'll use the shorter DNS names within the cluster.\n\nSince Prometheus is in the same namespace, I can reference the RabbitMQ pods directly using just the headless service DNS names without the full domain. Now I'll patch the ConfigMap and trigger the reload.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1990,"cache_read_input_tokens":32196,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1990},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"96b73c89-52ce-47b2-b4d6-f805ebfeac2a","uuid":"8c874809-ec37-42bb-b09f-e1c030c69a99","request_id":"req_011CcPyAQKX6CR5ZD3Yy5RzY"}
